Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Absolutely tragic news out of York County, with confirmation that five officers were shot and three have been killed.

These were not just officers in uniform. They were community members who, once again, chose to put themselves between danger and their neighbors, carrying a burden few would accept.

We cannot allow this to become routine. We cannot allow ourselves to grow numb. Violence, in any and every form, must be condemned at every level. Because every act of violence, no matter where it strikes or who it targets, tears at the fabric of our nation and the ties that hold us together.

May we honor the fallen and their families for their sacrifice, pray for a full recovery for the officers still fighting, support our neighbors in York County, and stand with the entire law enforcement community‚Äînot only in grief, but in daily, enduring gratitude.

And may we, as a nation, meet this moment with the seriousness it demands‚Äîsetting aside what divides us and remembering that we are stronger when we stand together, act with compassion, and show respect for one another. Unity is our greatest power and the only path forward.

In 1979, Nevada became the 34th state to formally call for an Article V Convention to propose a fiscal responsibility amendment, fulfilling the two-thirds constitutional requirement that should have triggered congressional action.
¬†
Yet Congress took no action to call the convention, leaving decades of state applications unanswered and stripping the states of their rightful authority to check runaway federal spending.
¬†
The Constitution provides a remedy when the federal government is unwilling or incapable of doing its job ‚Äì and that time for action is now.
¬†
That‚Äôs why I have introduced H.Con.Res.15 ‚Äì a resolution calling for an Article V Convention of the States to propose a fiscal responsibility amendment to the Constitution. This is about restoring accountability and ensuring the states can exercise the authority our Founders intended.

Hospitality and travel aren‚Äôt just about hotels and tourism‚Äîthey‚Äôre about people, jobs, and opportunity in our own backyard.

This week I sat down with Montu Patel of Doylestown and leaders from the @AAHOA to bring local constituent insight into the national conversation about the challenges facing independent hotel owners, small businesses, and hospitality workers.

We dug into how to strengthen small businesses, support the workforce, modernize policy, and make sure the hospitality sector stays competitive and sustainable, here in our community and across the country.

Big thanks to Montu and the AAHOA team for sharing your expertise‚ÄîI look forward to continuing working together to turn those perspectives into smart policy that grows opportunity, protects jobs, and makes our economy work better for everyone.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
The world has a moral and legal obligation to call atrocities by their name. What is happening in Gaza is genocide.

The Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide criminalizes acts committed with the intention to destroy a group in whole or in part. Leading experts and human rights organizations‚ÄîIsraeli, Palestinian, and international alike‚Äîcontinue to conclude that Israel‚Äôs actions in Gaza meet that legal threshold.

That conclusion is now reinforced by the determination of a United Nations Commission of Inquiry. Its findings are clear: Prime Minister Netanyahu must end his military operations and policy of starvation in Gaza. All states are obligated to take action to bring the genocide to an end.

As Co-Chair of the Tom Lantos Human Rights Commission, I have long argued that U.S. foreign policy must be grounded in international law and the defense of human dignity. Our country cannot turn a blind eye to such blatant violations of these principles. Nor can we continue to arm and fund a government engaged in such crimes.

The United States must forcefully demand an immediate ceasefire, the unimpeded delivery of humanitarian aid, a release of all hostages, and a diplomatic solution that secures safety and self-determination for both Israelis and Palestinians.

Once consistently ranked among the top states as recently as 2011, Maine now ranks near the bottom on national standardized tests, despite the very dedicated teachers and other educators we are fortunate to have in our state.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1995, the manifesto of Theodore Kaczynski, known as the Unabomber, was published by The New York Times and Washington Post to identify the individual responsible for a 17-year bombing campaign that killed three and injured 23. 

His bombing spree began in 1978, starting with an un-mailed package that injured a security guard. Over the next several years, Kaczynski mailed homemade pipe bombs to various targets, including executives at American and United Airlines and academic administrators, resulting in several injuries. The violence led to the death of a computer store owner in California. Ultimately, the Unabomber carried out 14 attacks with 16 bombs.

Kaczynski promised to halt his attacks if his manifesto was published in full by a major outlet. In his manifesto, Kaczynski contended that technology had distanced humans from nature. He advocated for a return to ‚Äúwild nature,‚Äù arguing that this necessitated an end to all scientific research.

Kaczynski's brother, David, recognized the writing style as that of Ted, who was later convicted and sentenced to life in prison without parole. His capture ended the FBI‚Äôs longest and most expensive manhunt.

Name: Self, Keith
text:
On National POW/MIA Recognition Day, we honor the extraordinary courage and sacrifice of prisoners of war (POWs) and those missing in action (MIA).

This day calls to mind heroes like former Texas Congressman Sam Johnson, who survived nearly seven years as a POW in Vietnam after his plane was shot down. Enduring solitary confinement in a tiny concrete cell‚Äîbound in leg irons and under constant light‚Äîhe never broke, emerging in 1973 as a symbol of the unbreakable American spirit. His legacy inspires us to keep fighting for those still listed as missing.

Name: Bell, Wesley
text:
The assassination of Charlie Kirk was an act of horrific political violence, and I condemn it without hesitation. My heart goes out to his wife, his children, and all who loved him. No family should ever endure this kind of tragedy. Political violence is a sickness that eats away at democracy and tears at the fabric of our society, and we must reject it in all its forms.

But condemning political violence does not require rewriting history. Mr. Kirk used his platform to demean, to divide, and to dehumanize many of the very people I represent. To honor his ‚Äòlife and legacy‚Äô in the congressional record would be to dishonor my constituents whose dignity he denied.

I cannot vote for a resolution that sanctifies a public figure who did not reciprocate respect for the lives, dignity and freedoms of others. What I can and will do is work to strengthen our democracy, protect all of our communities from violence, and ensure that every American is treated with respect.

That is the responsibility I owe my constituents, and it is the work I will continue to do.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug

Charlie was more than a political leader. He was a fighter for his beliefs, a mentor to young conservatives, and someone who never shied away from standing up for America‚Äôs values. His voice inspired thousands to get involved, and his legacy will continue to shape the future of our country.

This resolution honors his life and leadership. We can debate, we can disagree, but we cannot allow violence to silence voices or intimidate people into staying quiet. That is not who we are as a nation.

Name: Budzinski, Nikki
text:
Today, I joined my colleagues in condemning the horrific assassination of Charlie Kirk.

Political violence has no place in this country. If someone can be attacked for holding views you disagree with, then someone can just as easily be attacked for holding views you share. 

I know how frightening these times are ‚Äì each and every day members of Congress are faced with dangerous threats to their life, including myself. That‚Äôs why we must be united in condemning political violence, no matter our political beliefs.

I want to be clear: I did not agree with Charlie Kirk‚Äôs views. Too often, his engagement was neither civil nor respectful, and he supported ideas that are harmful and out of line with the values we should be building toward ‚Äì especially when it comes to women, the Black community, and the LGBTQ community.

My vote reflects my condemnation of political violence, period.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
‚ÄúPolitical violence has no place in our democracy, and I fully agree with the portions of the Charlie Kirk resolution that condemn it. In this moment, the most important outcome of today‚Äôs vote is that the House of Representatives went on record against political violence.

‚ÄúHowever, I strongly disagree with the way this resolution reads as an endorsement of Charlie Kirk‚Äôs worldview. We can condemn the violence committed against him while disagreeing with his positions and approach to political discourse.

‚ÄúIt would have been far better to pass a bipartisan resolution that clearly and unequivocally condemns all political violence‚Äîwhether from attacks on Speaker Pelosi, the attack on Minnesota House Speaker Hortman, or anywhere else‚Äîwithout turning it into a partisan effort.

‚ÄúEven with those serious reservations, I believe the condemnation of political violence is too important to ignore, which is why I supported that central principle in today‚Äôs vote.‚Äù

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Peace endures only when we choose it and fight to protect it. 

Since the UK passed its flawed Troubles bill in 2023, I‚Äôve worked with victims, families, and leaders in London, Dublin, Belfast, and here at home to help forge a path forward rooted in truth, accountability, and the rule of law.

This new framework is more than a course correction‚Äîit is a decisive step toward fulfilling the promise of the Good Friday Agreement, reopening investigations closed under the old act, reinforcing independent oversight, and most importantly, placing the victims and families back at the heart of the process.

This work reaches far beyond Northern Ireland. It speaks to our shared heritage, strengthens transatlantic ties, and offers a beacon of hope for divided societies everywhere. I will continue working with victims, families, leaders, and my colleagues in Congress to see this framework fully enacted and implemented. In doing so, we can ensure that reconciliation, not resentment, defines the next generation, and the United States remains a steadfast partner in this vital work.

Name: Perez, Marie Gluesenkamp
text:
I support the continuing resolution to keep the government open. 

With costs already shooting through the roof for families in Southwest Washington and across our country, I could not in good conscience vote to shut our government down, which would have made health care and food even more expensive for millions of Americans while handing the executive branch even more control over the nuts and bolts of the administrative apparatus. 

If you‚Äôre worried about families losing SNAP benefits and going hungry, research into cancer treatments for kids getting cut, or overworked air traffic controllers, you should be really concerned about the can of worms that a government shutdown would crack open.

It‚Äôs now been more than a year since Congress has passed an actual government funding bill. Continuing resolutions are the bare minimum ‚Äì we were sent here to do more than just keep the lights on. 

As we enter the next round of budget negotiations, I‚Äôll keep fighting as a member of the House Appropriations Committee for a real, bipartisan appropriations process that protects Americans‚Äô health care and builds an economy where folks only need to work one job to raise a family.

My own community on August 3,¬†2019,¬†was tragically impacted by political, domestic violence, and on January 6,¬†2021,¬†I was trapped in the House gallery as insurrectionists waving Trump and MAGA flags stormed the Capitol, assaulted police, and screamed 'Hang Mike Pence.'

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate neighbors from across our district, whose dedication and service make our community such a special place to call home. Today, we honor a man who has devoted his life to protecting and strengthening Newtown Township. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero‚Äî Fire Chief Glenn Forsyth.
 
Chief Forsyth‚Äôs story is woven into the fabric of Newtown itself. A lifelong resident, he grew up in a family where fire service wasn‚Äôt just a duty ‚Äî it was a tradition. His grandfather joined the Newtown Fire Association in 1915, his father and uncles followed, and in 1975, Glenn followed their footsteps, stepping up to become a junior firefighter. From that day forward, service wasn‚Äôt something he did; it became who he is.
 
Over the past five decades, he rose through the ranks of the Newtown Fire Association, serving as president, trustee, battalion chief, and safety officer, before being appointed in 2012 as Newtown Township‚Äôs first full-time fire chief, entrusted with leading and modernizing the department. Along the way, he mentored generations of firefighters and helped transform the department into the cornerstone of public safety it is today. This year marks not only his 50th year with the Newtown Fire Association but also his 47th year of service to Newtown Township, including 28 years with the police department. Through it all, he has been the very definition of a hometown public servant--dependable, humble, and devoted to his neighbors.
 
Through every chapter of his career, Chief Forsyth has been a steady presence‚Äîon the scene of emergencies, at community events, and behind the scenes, quietly improving safety, training, and preparedness. He has spent his life making his neighbors safer, his community stronger, and the Fire Association ready to serve the next generation.
 
Chief Forsyth‚Äôs career is more than a record of service‚Äîit‚Äôs a testament to his remarkable character. Please join me in thanking Chief Forsyth for 50 years of selfless service, leadership, and dedication to our community. Chief, we congratulate you on this incredible milestone and are proud to call you a true hometown hero!

Name: Perez, Marie Gluesenkamp
text:
Charlie Kirk was a human being. He was a human being with a family who loved him. We do not need to agree with the beliefs of everyone around us, but we do need to have the courage to see clearly how our hard heartedness, callousness, or indifference towards the humanity of others around us is tearing the country apart. We cannot simply call for unity or demand that others fix themselves without first addressing the ways that we have not lived up to our own standards. There cannot be unity and grace in this country until we as individuals confront our own shortcomings. 

I voted for the resolution to honor Charlie‚Äôs life ‚Äî but no legislation is going to bring him back or bring our country back together without each of us as individuals taking accountability for the ways that we have conformed to the brokenness of this world, for our fixation on the flaws rather than beauty of our brothers and sisters. 

None of us is promised a single minute on this earth. We have to turn to the serious work of diligently, deliberately, joyfully honoring the command to love each other.

Name: Morelle, Joseph D.
text:
Today I voted in favor of a resolution that, like many in Congress, is nuanced‚Äîand I know my decision may frustrate some people. Let me be clear: I did not agree with Charlie Kirk. His rhetoric was extremist, divisive, and often deeply harmful. I do not support language in this resolution that portrays him as noble or patriotic.
¬†
But democracy means that even people we strongly disagree with‚Äîpeople whose words make our blood boil‚Äîstill deserve the same rights and protections as everyone else. Freedom cannot be applied selectively.
¬†
At its core, this resolution condemns political violence, and that‚Äôs something we must all do‚Äîclearly and without hesitation. That is why I voted yes‚Äîand it‚Äôs why many of my colleagues did, too.
¬†
After the vote, I took a few moments to speak about my thought process and how, in the end, I decided to vote ‚Äúyes.‚Äù¬†I look forward to working with all my colleagues on policies to reject violence and restore civility to our politics.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1863, the Battle of Chickamauga ended in a Confederate victory. 

The Battle of Chickamauga occurred between the US Army of the Cumberland, led by Maj. Gen. William Rosecrans, and the Confederate Army of Tennessee, commanded by Gen. Braxton Bragg. Rosecrans aimed to drive the Confederates out of Chattanooga. In early September, he consolidated his forces and pushed Bragg's army south.

Bragg sought to retake Chattanooga, intending to strike Rosecrans‚Äôs isolated troops. A miscommunication led Rosecrans to create an actual gap in his defenses, which Confederate Lt. Gen. James Longstreet exploited, resulting in a rout of Union forces. The Union ultimately retreated to Chattanooga, while the Confederates took control of the surrounding heights, besieging the city.

This battle was notable as the first major conflict in Georgia and represented the largest Union defeat in the Western Theater, resulting in the second-highest number of casualties after Gettysburg.

Name: Harrigan, Pat
text:
I'm watching speaker after speaker honor Charlie Kirk, and what I'm witnessing represents something far more significant than a funeral service.

We are not simply mourning the loss of a conservative leader, we are observing the emergence of a new generation of American patriots who understand that the future of our republic now rests in their hands.

Charlie Kirk demonstrated what becomes possible when one individual refuses to surrender their convictions to the forces of political correctness and cultural decay. He possessed the moral clarity to speak uncomfortable truths when others remained silent. He had the courage to stand firm when others retreated. He inspired millions of Americans to reclaim their voice, defend their values, and fight for their country. And the young leaders who carry his torch today understand that failure is not an option.

The radical left and their allies in the establishment better understand this: what Charlie built cannot be torn down by cancel culture, cannot be destroyed by media attacks, and cannot be defeated by political persecution. It is built on the solid foundation of faith in God, commitment to truth, and love of country.

Charlie understood what too many in Washington have forgotten‚Äîthat politics is not about personal ambition or partisan advantage. Politics is about preserving the constitutional principles that made America exceptional. Politics is about ensuring that our children inherit a nation where freedom still means something.

His message was clear and uncompromising: Build strong families. Raise patriotic children. Defend our institutions. Pass down our values. Choose principle over convenience, truth over popularity, courage over comfort.

That is Charlie Kirk's enduring legacy. That is the foundation upon which the next generation of conservative leaders will stand.

Today we honor a patriot. Tomorrow we continue his work.

"Well done, good and faithful servant." ‚Äî Matthew 25:21

Name: Cole, Tom
text:
Today, a memorial service was held for Charlie Kirk in Arizona. Following the service, I released the following statement: 
¬†
Charlie Kirk was a good man. He was a dedicated Christian, who allowed his faith to guide him in all he did. He was a true patriot who loved the United States of America with all his heart. He believed in strong family values and was a devoted husband to his wife, Erika, and father to his two children. He was a leader and mentor to many with the talented ability to connect with the American people, particularly the youth, through his public speaking skills and successful conservative nonprofit, Turning Point USA.
¬†
Charlie believed in the importance of civil discourse and public debate. When Charlie visited college campuses, he was not there to give speeches and presentations. Instead, he was there to respectfully take questions from students ‚Äì no matter what side of the political aisle they were on ‚Äì and try to find understanding of one another. In fact, I was looking forward to welcoming Charlie to my district this fall, as he was scheduled to be at the University of Oklahoma in Norman on October 16. Now, we unfortunately won‚Äôt get that opportunity.
¬†
Yet, it was in this exact setting, while he was in the literal act of public dialogue, that Charlie was assassinated. It is just sick, tragic, and harrowing. It fills me with grief, not only for his family, friends, and Turning Point USA colleagues, but for our entire nation, as political violence of any kind is never acceptable and, quite frankly, is un-American.
¬†
I have full faith in Director Kash Patel, the FBI, and Utah law enforcement as they actively work to bring justice to Charlie Kirk. However, we, as Americans, should also honor his legacy by engaging in genuine civil debate with those on the other side of the aisle, allowing faith and strong family values to guide us in our lives daily, spreading Charlie‚Äôs strong conservative message, and by coming together as a nation to fight back against the evil that exists in this country.
¬†
I am confident that we will overcome this dark chapter. In the meantime, please join me in praying for the soul of Charlie Kirk, his family, his friends, his fans, and our country. May Charlie Kirk rest in peace.

It‚Äôs been truly moving to witness the countless number of people from across the country come together to honor the life and legacy of Charlie Kirk. Charlie was more than a devoted husband, father, and Conservative activist. He was, above all, a man of deep Christian faith with comprehensive knowledge of the Scripture. He dedicated his life to spreading the message of Christ and empowering the next generation to think for themselves and stand up for their beliefs.

Charlie ignited a movement, inspiring countless young Americans to engage and get involved. That legacy was on full display during Sunday‚Äôs powerful memorial in Arizona with people traveling from across the nation to pay their respects and listen to the tributes from Charlie‚Äôs pastor, Vice President J.D. Vance, President Trump, and Charlie‚Äôs widow, Erika Kirk. Erika‚Äôs words, especially her forgiveness of the man who took her husband‚Äôs life, were a profound testament to her strength grounded in unshakable faith. Erika will do a great job carrying on Charlie‚Äôs mission at Turning Point USA.

Thank you to everyone who has shared kind words and memories of Charlie. His legacy and influence will continue to grow with each passing day.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
This weekend in Universal City, I joined veterans, military families, community partners, and local leaders to celebrate the 50th anniversary of American Legion Post 667. For half a century, Post 667 has been a pillar of honor, service, and fellowship, providing veterans with support, strengthening families, and instilling the values of duty and patriotism in future generations.

As your U.S. Representative, I remain committed to ensuring our veterans receive the care and resources they deserve. I was proud to cosponsor the PACT Act, now law, which expands healthcare benefits for veterans exposed to toxic substances. I also supported the Disabled Veterans Housing Support Act, which passed in the House, to ensure disabled veterans are not unfairly disqualified from housing assistance. This year‚Äôs appropriations bill includes billions for veterans programs, from housing and childcare to mental health services and support for homeless veterans.

I want to thank American Legion Post 667 for 50 years of sacrifice, fellowship, and devotion to community. Congratulations on this historic milestone, and may the next 50 years continue to bring strength, service, and unity to Universal City and beyond. üá∫üá∏

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
What an honor to celebrate the remarkable Jean Spencer Batten, one of PA-1‚Äôs most special treasures and the @Phillies' #1 fan, on her 100th birthday!

Born in Northampton, England in 1925, Jean met U.S. Air Force serviceman Robert Batten at a dance in while he was stationed in London during WWII. They married in September 1946 and set sail on a seven-day transatlantic journey to begin their American dream in Bucks County. Bob built their home in Bensalem with his own hands, and together they raised a beautiful family, filling their days with laughter, love, faith, and adventure until his passing in 1997.

When asked her secret to a long, happy life? Jean replied: ‚ÄúA green vegetable at every dinner. One cookie to ‚Äòcue the end of the meal.‚Äô And a gin & tonic at 3 PM on Saturdays and Sundays.

Please join me in celebrating Jean, and wishing her a very happy 100th birthday!

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
A lot of people might not get their news from the internet. But the people THEY get their news from‚Äîjournalists, pundits, talk-show hosts‚Äîdo. It's where the conversation starts.

Throughout the 2010s, much of the Right didn't even have full access to the conversation at all.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
That's a refrain you heard from all the elite left-wing censorship cheerleaders, over and over again: "Deplatforming works."

They were right. Turns out, when you make it impossible for your opponents to speak, argue, or challenge your narrative‚Äîit's actually pretty effective! https://t.co/FjkIJdB9bQ

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: But things are changing. Everyone can see and feel it. The Left is still incredibly powerful‚Äîwe shouldn't be naive about that in the fights ahead‚Äîbut their grip is slipping. They no longer have a stranglehold over the political narrative. And their censorship regime is crumbling.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: They're getting beat by new media, new creators, new platforms‚Äîoutmaneuvered by people with better ideas and arguments, who are far more adept at navigating the new digital landscape. All of that became possible because the internet is simply more free than it was 5 years ago.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
I vividly remember how extreme the left-wing censorship was, just a few short years ago. As AG of Missouri, I led the fight to sue the Biden administration for pressuring tech platforms into censoring conservatives‚Äîand took them to the Supreme Court.

text:

We're just better at this than they are.

We've come a long way since then. The Left has lost a lot of big battles. The momentum is on our side.
